This document is NOT a legal license.

The only legally binding license for the MultiPixel ecosystem is:

    /LICENSE
    MultiPixel Source-Available License 2.2 — Fortress Edition

This Governance License Router exists to:
• map the governance structure
• route readers to the correct folders
• provide a deep-dive index into all governance areas
• ensure all governance documents remain subordinate to the root license
• prevent duplication, contradictions, or legal drift

All documents referenced below inherit their authority from the root license.
No governance document overrides or replaces the root license.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ROOT GOVERNANCE STRUCTURE
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

Governance/
 ├── Compliance/
 ├── Ecosystem/
 ├── Guidelines/
 ├── Policies/
 ├── Requirements/
 ├── Forms/
 ├── Notices/
 └── Guides/

Each section below routes to the correct subfolders and documents.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMPLIANCE/
    Purpose: Enforceable rules, obligations, and penalties.

    Subfolders:
        Compliance/Monetization/
        Compliance/Servers/
        Compliance/Mods/
        Compliance/Branding/
        Compliance/Data/
        Compliance/Audits/
        Compliance/Violations/

    Each subfolder contains:
        - *_Compliance_Rules
        - *_Standards
        - *_Requirements
        - *_Audit_Procedures
        - *_Violation_Categories
        - *_Penalty_Tiers

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

ECOSYSTEM/
    Purpose: High-level descriptions of how the MultiPixel ecosystem works.

    Subfolders:
        Ecosystem/Overview/
        Ecosystem/Roles/
        Ecosystem/Architecture/
        Ecosystem/Workflows/
        Ecosystem/Lifecycle/
        Ecosystem/Systems/
        Ecosystem/Governance/
        Ecosystem/Glossary/

    These documents are descriptive, not enforceable.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

GUIDELINES/
    Purpose: Recommended best practices (non-enforceable).

    Subfolders:
        Guidelines/Global/
        Guidelines/Server/
        Guidelines/Mod/
        Guidelines/Community/
        Guidelines/Safety/
        Guidelines/Conduct/
        Guidelines/Content/
        Guidelines/Branding/
        Guidelines/BestPractices/

    These documents support but do not replace Compliance or Policies.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

POLICIES/
    Purpose: Enforceable behavior, safety, and operational policies.

    Subfolders:
        Policies/Safety/
        Policies/Moderation/
        Policies/Content/
        Policies/Platform/
        Policies/Legal/

    Policies must always align with the root license and Compliance rules.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

REQUIREMENTS/
    Purpose: Mandatory technical and operational requirements.

    Subfolders:
        Requirements/Servers/
        Requirements/Mods/
        Requirements/Branding/
        Requirements/Data/
        Requirements/Monetization/

    Requirements define what must be done, not how.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

FORMS/
    Purpose: Official submission and reporting forms.

    Subfolders:
        Forms/Server/
        Forms/User/
        Forms/Business/
        Forms/Other/

    Forms must match the structure defined in Compliance and Policies.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

NOTICES/
    Purpose: Public notices, warnings, and administrative messages.

    Subfolders:
        Notices/Legal/
        Notices/Security/
        Notices/Updates/
        Notices/Enforcement/

    Notices communicate changes but do not override the root license.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

GUIDES/
    Purpose: Practical, step-by-step “how to” documents that help users,
             server owners, developers, and staff correctly implement
             Governance, Compliance, Policies, and Requirements.

    Recommended subfolders:
        Guides/Servers/
        Guides/Mods/
        Guides/Monetization/
        Guides/Moderation/
        Guides/Safety/
        Guides/Branding/
        Guides/Onboarding/

    Example documents:
        Guides/Servers/How_to_Set_Up_a_Compliant_Server
        Guides/Mods/How_to_Submit_a_Mod
        Guides/Monetization/How_to_Enable_Compliant_Monetization
        Guides/Moderation/How_to_Handle_Reports_and_Appeals
        Guides/Safety/How_to_Respond_to_Safety_Issues

    Guides are instructional and supportive. They:
        - do NOT create new rules
        - do NOT override Compliance, Policies, or Requirements
        - MUST stay consistent with the root license and other governance areas

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

FINAL DECLARATION
All governance documents:
• are subordinate to the root license
• must not contradict the root license
• must not introduce new permissions not granted by the root license
• must not weaken any restriction defined in the root license
• must be updated when the root license changes

If a governance document is missing, incomplete, or outdated:
• the root license takes precedence
• the missing document must be created before enforcement
• no rule may be enforced unless it exists in writing

